    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-12-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-12-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="278"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d278">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760C.61/977: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Kuibyshev</hi> (<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >Moscow</hi>)</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-12-06"
                            >December 6, 1941</date>.<lb/>[Received December 6—4 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2018. The following official statement was published in <hi rend="italic"
                        >Pravda</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Izvestiya</hi> December 5th.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“As a result of negotiations which took place in Moscow on December 3 and 4
                        between Stalin and Molotov on the one hand and General Sikorski and Polish
                        Ambassador Kot on the other, a declaration of the Governments of the Soviet
                        Union and the Polish Republic concerning friendship and mutual assistance
                        was signed on December 4 by Stalin and General Sikorski for their respective
                        Governments. The text of the declaration is as follows:</p>
                    <p>The Government of the Soviet Union and the Government of the Polish Republic,
                        imbued with the spirit of friendly agreement and of militant cooperation,
                        declare that:</p>
                    <p>1. German Hitlerite imperialism is the worst enemy of mankind and no
                        compromise whatever with it is possible.</p>
                    <p>Both states, together with Great Britain and other Allies and with support
                        from the United States of America, will conduct the war unto complete
                        victory and the conclusive annihilation of the German aggressors.</p>
                    <p>2. In fulfillment of the treaty concluded on July 30, 1941, the two
                        Governments shall render full military assistance to one another during the
                        time of the war and the troops of the Polish Republic located on the
                        territory of the Soviet Union will hand in hand with the Soviet troops
                        conduct war against the German bandits.</p>
                    <p>In time of peace the basis of their relations will be good neighborly
                        cooperation, friendship and mutual honest fulfillment of the obligations
                        which they shall nave assumed.</p>
                    <p>3. After the victorious war and the appropriate punishment of the Hitlerite
                        criminals, the task of the Allied States will be to assure a lasting and
                        just peace. This can be attained only by a new organization of international
                        relations, organization which is based upon the unification of democratic
                        countries in a lasting alliance. In the creation <pb facs="0279" n="267"
                            xml:id="pg_267"/> of such organization the decisive factor should be
                        respect for international law supported by the collective armed forces of
                        all Allied States. Only on this condition can the Europe being ruined by the
                        German barbariacs [<hi rend="italic">barbarians</hi>] be restored, and can a
                        guarantee be made that the catastrophe caused by the Hitlerites will never
                        be repeated.”</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Thurston</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
